==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Till
<hw>Till</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. from
<ets>lentil</ets>.]</ety> <def>A vetch; a tare.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Till</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Till
<hw>Till</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Properly, a drawer, from OE.
<ets>tillen</ets> to draw. See <er>Tiller</er> the lever of a
rudder.]</ety> <def>A drawer.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A
tray or drawer in a chest.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A money drawer in a
shop or store.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Till alarm</b></col>, <cd>a device for sounding an alarm
when a money drawer is opened or tampered with.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Till</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Till
<hw>Till</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A
deposit of clay, sand, and gravel, without lamination, formed in a
glacier valley by means of the waters derived from the melting glaciers;
-- sometimes applied to alluvium of an upper river terrace, when not
laminated, and appearing as if formed in the same manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of coarse, obdurate land.</def>
<rj><au>Loudon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Till</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Till
<hw>Till</hw>, <pos>prep.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>til</ets>, Icel.
<ets>til</ets>; akin to Dan. <ets>til</ets>, Sw. <ets>till</ets>,
OFries. <ets>til</ets>, also to AS. <ets>til</ets> good, excellent, G.
<ets>ziel</ets> end, limit, object, OHG. <ets>zil</ets>, Goth.
<ets>tils</ets>, ga<ets>tils</ets>, fit, convenient, and E.
<ets>till</ets> to cultivate. See <er>Till</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<def>To; unto; up to; as far as; until; -- now used only in respect to
time, but formerly, also, of place, degree, etc., and still so used in
Scotland and in parts of England and Ireland; <as>as, I worked
<ex>till</ex> four o'clock; I will wait <ex>till</ex> next
week.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . came <qex>till</qex> an house.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Women, up <qex>till</qex> this⟦br⟧
Cramped under worse than South-sea-isle taboo.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Similar sentiments will recur to every one familiar with his
writings -- all through them <qex>till</qex> the very end.</q>
<rj><qau>Prof. Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Till now</b></col>, <cd>to the present time.</cd> --
<col><b>Till then</b></col>, <cd>to that time.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1509 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Till</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Till
<hw>Till</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>conj.</pos> <def>As far as; up to the
place or degree that; especially, up to the time that; that is, to the
time specified in the sentence or clause following; until.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And said unto them, Occupy <qex>till</qex> I come.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke xix. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mediate so long <qex>till</qex> you make some act of prayer to
God.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was no outbreak <qex>till</qex> the regiment arrived.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This use may be explained by supposing an ellipsis of
<xex>when</xex>, or <xex>the time when</xex>, the proper conjunction or
conjunctive adverb begin <xex>when</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Till</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Till
<hw>Till</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tilled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tilling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>tilen</ets>,
<ets>tilien</ets>, AS. <ets>tilian</ets>, <ets>teolian</ets>, to aim,
strive for, till; akin to OS. <ets>tilian</ets> to get, D.
<ets>telen</ets> to propagate, G. <ets>zielen</ets> to aim,
<ets>ziel</ets> an end, object, and perhaps also to E. <ets>tide</ets>,
<ets>time</ets>, from the idea of something fixed or definite. Cf.
<er>Teal</er>, <er>Till</er>, <pos>prep.</pos>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To plow and prepare for seed, and to sow, dress, raise crops from,
etc., to cultivate; <as>as, to <ex>till</ex> the earth, a field, a
farm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No field nolde [would not] <qex>tilye</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>P.
Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>the Lord God sent him forth from the garden of Eden, to
<qex>till</qex> the ground from whence he was taken.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
iii. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To prepare; to get.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>W. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Till</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Till
<hw>Till</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cultivate land.</def>
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tillable</ent>⟦br⟧
